\frametitle{ Example Proof by Induction }

{\bf Proposition} If $n\in\nats$, then $1+3+5+7 +...+(2n-1) = n^2$.

(1) If $n=1$, then $1=1^2$, which is true.

(2) Assume $1+3+5+7 +...+(2k-1) = k^2$ for some $k\in\nats$.

Then
\begin{align*}
  1+3+5+7 +... + 2(k+1) -1 &= \\
  1+3+5+7 +...+(2k-1) + (2(k+1) -1) &= k^2 + (2(k+1) -1)\\
  &= k^2 + 2d + 1\\
  &= (k+1)^2
\end{align*}
\QED

